▪ wilful misconduct of insured;
▪ ordinary leakage, loss of weight or volume, wear and tear;
▪ unsuitable packing;
▪ inherent vice;
▪ delay;
▪ insolvency or financial default of the owners managers charterers or operators of the vessel where, at the time of loading of the subject-matter insured on board the vessel, the insured is aware, or in the ordinary course of business should be aware, that such insolvency or financial default could prevent the normal prosecution of the voyage;
▪ use of any weapon or device employing atomic or nuclear fission or radioactive force or matter; or
▪ deliberate damage to or destruction of subject matter insured.

An Open Cover is essentially an agreement between the insured and the insurer to cover all the shipments which fall within the terms and conditions as agreed by both parties. The insured will give the broad perimeters of the risk to be covered, such as:
▪ nature of cargo and packaging;
▪ mode of transit;
▪ details of voyages to be made; and
▪ maximum value of cargoes carried in any one shipment.

Here are the following claim documents which need to be submitted to the insurer to substantiate a loss under a Marine Cargo Insurance policy:
▪ whatever document was originally issued to substantiate the insurance placed – this could be the original copy of the policy or certificate of insurance;
▪ Airway Bill, Bill of Lading, transhipment Bill of Lading or railway freight note, when applicable;
▪ original shipper’s invoice; 5A bill of lading is the document “issued” by the carrier and given to the shipper in acknowledgement of goods having been loaded on board a vessel. (In reality, it has probably already been prepared by a shipping agent/customs agent based on negotiations for cargo space, and has then been validated by the carrier’s agent.)
▪ packaging list, weight certificates or other evidence of the nature and conditions of the goods at the time of shipment;
▪ Port/Airport Authority’s Cargo Irregularity Report or Inward Report – this document would prove that the cargo was damaged during transit, and could give some indication as to which stage of the voyage that the damage occurred;
▪ copy of the survey/joint survey report and original photographs, where applicable;
▪ repair/reinstatement invoices;
▪ original delivery note or other original document of receipt from the forwarder/transporter; and
▪ statement of claim to the carriers/bailees and their replies.

Other items that are specifically covered are as follows:
▪ items at other premises in the same port (once allocated);
▪ sea trials (up to 250 miles or 402 km);
▪ launching failure;
▪ protection and indemnity;
▪ collision liability;
▪ general average;
▪ salvage; and
▪ sue and labour expenses.

The following risks are principally excluded under a Builder’s Risks Insurance:
▪ earthquake (but it is quite common to see this exclusion deleted by agreement);
▪ volcanic eruption;
▪ cost of renewing faulty welds;
▪ liability in respect of compensation for employees;
▪ punitive and exemplary damages; and
▪ pollution or contamination.

Insurers will normally require the following information for underwriting:
▪ estimated contract value;
▪ estimated period of construction;
▪ type of vessel being constructed;
▪ yard claims history;
▪ deductible level;
▪ launch, trials and delivery details; and
▪ additional covers.

Marine Liabilities Insurance includes, among others:
▪ Ship Repairer’s Liability Insurance;
▪ Charterers’ Liability Insurance;
▪ Port Authorities Liability Insurance;
▪ Stevedore Liability Insurance; and
▪ Terminal Operators’ Liability Insurance.

A Ship Repairer’s Liability Insurance policy covers:
▪ vessels which are in the care, custody or control of the ship repairer for the purpose of being worked upon against the risks of fire damage, explosion, contact damage and machinery damage;
▪ cargo and other property aboard a vessel under repair or discharged from a vessel to facilitate repairs against similar risks to the vessel itself, as well as the risks of theft, pilferage and deterioration;
▪ third-party liabilities, including personal injury and loss of life;
▪ liability for wreck removal which may arise out of ship repairing activities;
▪ contractual liability assumed by the ship repairer as hirers of tugs, tenders, or other craft in connection with his ship repair activities;
▪ liability pertaining to other work undertaken by the ship repairer and which does not fall under the definition of ship repairing; and
▪ legal liability for detention of a vessel which may arise from the consequences of loss of or damage to that vessel while under repair.

The general underwriting information to be obtained is as follows:
▪ number, type, tonnage, etc. of vessels handled per annum;
▪ gross receipts and/or payroll per annum;
▪ number of employees;
▪ whether reconstruction of vessels is carried out and, if so, whether it is major and what percentage of total operations that it comprises;
▪ whether there is any onshore exposure involved, i.e. fabrication yards, railways, heavy construction/assembly work, etc;
▪ any “hot work” on tankers and vessels of similar type is being carried out;
▪ location of yards;
▪ details of standard contract used by yard;
▪ details of yard’s facilities, i.e. number of wet/dry docks, piers, wharves, etc;
▪ limit of liability required; and
▪ record of past claims or losses.

The general underwriting information to be obtained is as follows:
▪ name of vessel(s);
▪ limit of liability required;
▪ whether the charter is only for a single voyage, or for a period of time;
▪ period of charter;
▪ number of voyages;
▪ length of contracts;
▪ type of cargoes carried;
▪ ports of loading/discharge;
▪ loading/discharge methods;
▪ the person responsible for stevedoring;
▪ whether cargo is owned by the charterer or by third parties;
▪ Is cover required in respect of Liability to Cargo?
▪ Is vessel space-chartered? If so, for what percentage of space? and
▪ details of claims or losses in respect of Charterer’s Liability during the last five years.

A Port Authorities Liability Insurance policy covers:
▪ vessels, regardless of whether they are owned by, chartered or operated by the Port Authority, against risk of physical damage;
▪ property at risk on an “All Risk” basis which includes loss, damage or expense arising from fire, lightning, explosion, aircraft impact, storm, electrical and mechanical breakdown, etc;
▪ employer’s liability or work injury compensation;
▪ third-party liabilities, including personal injury and loss of life, and physical damage to property;
▪ liability for wreck removal which can be incurred by the port authority, following a loss stemming from fault of services or facilities as provided by the port authority; and
▪ additional expenses incurred to protect the environment or to restore its natural resources, following an incident within the port.

The general underwriting information to be obtained is as follows:
▪ name and address of port authority;
▪ location of all ports within the port authority’s area of control;
▪ plans showing details of port authority’s area of control and also relationship to third-party property;
▪ details of all activities and operations of the port authority including: - whether they own or operate vessels of any kind (e.g. tugs, pilot launches, crane barges, etc.); - whether they handle or store cargo; - whether they are responsible for berthing and unberthing vessels; - whether they are responsible to maintain channels and berth, dredged to certain depth; and - whether they own or operate vehicles.
▪ details of all contracts entered into by the port authority;
▪ whether port authority provides bunkering, fuelling or victualling facilities;
▪ range of numbers, sizes, types, etc. of vessels using the port and type of cargo loaded and discharged and annual tonnage;
▪ annual revenues and payrolls;
▪ number of employees on port authority payroll;
▪ approximate value of cargo in port at any one time;
▪ types of storage facilities owned or operated by port authority;
▪ main nationalities of vessels calling at port; and
▪ claims record for last five years.

Therefore, Stevedores' Liability Insurance includes cover for liability as a result of:
▪ cargo lost, damaged, misdirected, delayed or wrongfully delivered;
▪ ship lost or damaged;
▪ third-party property damaged; and
▪ loss of life or bodily injury; where such liability occurs in the course of or arises from its stevedoring operations.

The information required by the insurer is as follows:
▪ nature of services provided to customers;
▪ professional qualifications or number of years experience of insured’s directors, partners or senior managers;
▪ number and percentage of own full-time manual employees;
▪ number and percentage of independent stevedores contracted;
▪ quality assurance accreditation from any internationally recognised organisation;
▪ annual turnover;
▪ cargo/tonnage handled;
▪ methods of handling bulk cargoes;
▪ type and packing;
▪ claims history; and
▪ trading conditions, i.e. (a) standard contracts? (b) individual user agreements? and (c) no contract?

Common causes of losses to be indemnified under a CAR Insurance policy include:
▪ fire, lightning, explosion, aircraft crashing, water from fire extinguishers or other fire-fighting measures;
▪ flood, inundation, windstorm of any kind;
▪ theft, burglary; and
▪ resultant loss or damage owing to bad workmanship, lack of skill, negligence, malicious act, or human error1.

Subject to any individual insurer’s policy wording, the policy may extend to cover the following items:
▪ contractors’ equipment materials and mobile equipment at site;
▪ temporary works;
▪ existing structure or property;
▪ materials stored at site;
▪ fabrication at a different site; and
▪ clearance of debris2.

The following are exclusions applicable to most construction projects. However, they can be covered in the policy by payment of additional premiums:
▪ deductible to be borne by the insured in any one occurrence;
▪ consequential loss of any kind or description whatsoever, including any penalty, loss owing to delay, lack of performance, loss of contract;
▪ loss or damage owing to faulty design; and
▪ cost of replacement, repair or rectification of defective material and/or workmanship. 2 Clearance of debris includes costs and expenses necessarily and reasonably incurred by the insured in removing debris, shoring up or propping, dismantling and/or demolishing, and clearance or repairing of drains and services, following loss or damage to the property insured by any cause not excluded by the policy.

The other exclusions relating to Section I – Material Damage, which cannot be removed even with payment of additional premiums, are:
▪ wear and tear, corrosion, oxidation, deterioration owing to lack of use and normal atmospheric conditions;
▪ mechanical and/or electrical breakdown or derangement of construction plant, equipment and construction machinery;
▪ loss or damage to vehicles licensed for general road use or water borne vessels or aircraft (as these are usually covered under other classes of insurance);
▪ loss of or damage to files, drawings, accounts, bills, currency, stamps, deeds, evidences of debt, notes, securities, cheques; and
▪ loss or damage discovered only at the time of tracking an inventory.

The exclusions applicable to Section II – Third-Party Liability are as follows:
▪ deductible to be borne by the insured in any one occurrence;
▪ expenditure incurred in redoing or repairing or replacing anything covered or coverable under Section I of the CAR Insurance policy;
▪ injury to any person or damage to any property caused by vibration, removal or weakening of support (unless especially agreed upon by endorsement);
▪ liability consequent upon bodily injury to or illness of employees or workmen of the contractor(s) or the principal(s), or any other firm connected with the project;
▪ liability consequent upon loss of or damage to property belonging to or held in care, custody or control of the contractor(s), the principal(s) or any other firm connected with the project;
▪ any accident caused by vehicles licensed for general road use or by waterborne vessels or aircraft; and
▪ any agreement by the insured to pay any sum by way of indemnity or otherwise, unless such liability would have attached in the absence of such agreement.

Besides effecting a CAR Insurance policy, there may be other types of related insurance protection which the insured needs to consider, such as:
▪ Project Professional Indemnity (PI) Cover;
▪ Work Injury Compensation Cover;
▪ Construction Business Interruption Cover; and
▪ Performance Bond.

The testing and commissioning work may involve:
▪ testing of various kinds;
▪ commissioning, i.e. initial operation; maintenance, i.e. rectification of any defect manifested during the maintenance period;
▪ staff training; and
▪ operation of the completed works.

This type of equipment can generally be classified into two groups, i.e. Stationary equipment, such as:
▪ Tower Cranes;
▪ Conveyer Systems;
▪ Passenger Lifts;
▪ Elevators;
▪ Hoists. Movable equipment, such as:
▪ Mobile Cranes;
▪ Gantry Cranes;
▪ Forklifts;
▪ Loaders;
▪ Loading Shovels;
▪ Excavators.

The main determinants of CPE risk exposure are:
▪ the operational condition at the worksite where the lifting equipment is used;
▪ nature and condition of the plant and equipment;
▪ size and structure of the organisation that owns and / or operates the equipment; and
▪ loss experience.

The policy provides indemnity against:
▪ damage to the boiler or other insured items;
▪ damage to other property of the insured directly owing to explosion and collapse of any insured item;
▪ liability of the insured at law for damage to property not belonging to the insured; and
▪ liability of the insured at law in respect of fatal or non-fatal injuries to any persons, other than the insured’s own employees or workers, or members of the insured’s family.

The subject matter for Boiler & Pressure Vessel Insurance is the plant or other property belonging to the insured or held by the insured in trust or on commission. (a) Plant It refers to “those parts of the permanent structure which are subject to steam or other fluid pressure, up to and including fittings and direct attachments, subject to such pressure and which are connected to the permanent structure without an intervening valve or cock”. It also means “the metal parts of pressure and water gauges and their connections to the permanent structure even if separated from such structure by valves or cocks”. It does not mean (except where specifically described in the schedule of the policy):
▪ superheaters or economisers;
▪ feed circulating supply or delivery piping or anything connected to it. (b) Explosion It means “the sudden and violent rending of the permanent structure of the plant by force of internal steam or fluid pressure (other than pressure of ignited gases) causing bodily displacement of any part of the structure, together with the forcible ejection of its contents.” (c) Collapse It means “the sudden and dangerous distortion (whether or not attended by rupture) of any part of the plant caused by the crushing stress of external steam or other fluid pressure (other than pressure of ignited flue gases).”

The customarily required underwriting information is as follows:
▪ description of the plant, including its age, type, model, capacity, working pressure, whether a fire-tube or water-tube, the materials used and the method of construction;
▪ whether the plant is fully attended, partly attended, or unattended;
▪ whether there is regular maintenance performed;
▪ the type of fuel used (this information is pertinent to flue gas explosions);
▪ whether the plant requires certification – if the relevant plant is registered, what is the registered number?
▪ sum insured for each item;
▪ public liability considerations;
▪ exposure to risk of surrounding property; and
▪ if boilers are used for domestic purposes, is the explosion risk insured by a fire policy?

The following risks may be included in the scope of the policy on payment of extra premiums:
▪ repairs to overheating of tubes;
▪ repairs to overheating of boilers and fired pressure vessel;
▪ fuel gas explosion;
▪ sudden cracking or fracturing of hot water boiler;
▪ leakage damage arising from the cracking of the heating and hot water boilers; and
▪ general damage, such as accidental causes to parts of the plant under pressure.

Loss or damage covered under Machinery Breakdown Insurance may be due to any of the following causes: (a) "internal" causes such as:
▪ defective material, design, construction or erection;
▪ vibration, maladjustment, misalignment, loosening of parts;
▪ abnormal stresses, fatigue, centrifugal forces, self-heating;
▪ defective or inadequate lubrication;
▪ excessive electrical current or voltage;
▪ failure of insulation, short circuits, open circuits or arcing;
▪ failure of protecting, measuring or regulating devices;
▪ failure of or fault in connected machines; and
▪ water hammer/knocking or overheating, except in the case of boilers or similar machinery when followed by explosion. (b) "external" causes such as:
▪ errors, lack of skills, negligence, or wilful acts of employees or third parties;
▪ falling, impact, collision or similar occurrence, obstruction or the entry of foreign bodies;
▪ storm, frost or drifting ice; and
▪ any other causes not excluded by the policy.

The customarily required underwriting information is as follows:
▪ description of the machinery including size, capacity, model, date of manufacture, history of breakdown, and so on;
▪ the repair facilities;
▪ the extent of maintenance or servicing;
▪ the general housekeeping and working environment, including business efficiency;
▪ the extent of obsolescence, if any;
▪ the availability of replacement parts, particularly so, if it is of foreign manufacture;
▪ the territorial location;
▪ the claims history in relation to the insured machinery; and
▪ the sums insured.

Other than the usual general exceptions that relate to war, strike, riot, civil commotion and nuclear risks, some common exclusions specific to this class of insurance are as follows:
▪ deductible to be borne by the insured in respect of loss of or damage to each item;
▪ damage owing to fire, direct lightning, explosion, aircraft or other aerial devices or articles dropped therefrom, collapse of buildings, inundation, flood, earthquake, subsidence, landslide, burglary and theft, and consequential loss;
▪ loss of or damage to exchangeable tools, e.g. dies, moulds, parts which by their use and/or nature suffer a high rate of wear and depreciation, e.g. refractory linings, objects made of glass, ropes, wheels, elevator, conveyor belts, cables other than electrical conductors, brushes, batteries, tyres, lubricants, fuel;
▪ wear and tear as a direct consequence of ordinary use or operation, such as cavitation, erosion, corrosion, rust, boiler scale;
▪ consequential loss or liability of any kind or description, any payments over and above the indemnity for material damage as provided under the insurance; and
▪ loss or damage caused by any fault or defect existing at the time of commencement of the insurance known to the insured.

Examples of some of the many extensions available in Machinery Breakdown Insurance include:
▪ renewal of refrigerant necessitated by the breakdown of air-conditioning and refrigerant plant;
▪ damage to goods being lifted;
▪ deterioration of stock in the refrigerating machinery;
▪ surrounding property damage; and
▪ expediting expenses, such as wages for overtime, payment for carriage by express rail, or road transport, or by air freight, for expediting repairs of damage to the insured plant or property.

The common exclusions in a Deterioration of Stock policy include:
▪ applicable excesses;
▪ loss due to shrinkage;
▪ inherent defects or disease;
▪ natural deterioration/putrefaction;
▪ improper storage;
▪ damage to packing material;
▪ insufficient circulation of air;
▪ non-uniformity of temperature;
▪ temporary repair of the refrigeration machinery without the insurer’s consent;
▪ consequential loss;
▪ penalties for delay;
▪ war risks;
▪ nuclear radioactive contamination;
▪ wilful act and negligence; and
▪ fire, lightning, chemical explosion, aircraft damage, theft, collapse of a building, flood, convulsion of nature.

The types of bonds commonly issued by insurers are:
▪ Advance Payment Bonds;
▪ Bid Bonds;
▪ Credit Bonds
▪ Security Bonds;
▪ Licence & Permit Bonds;
▪ Maintenance Bonds;
▪ Payment Bonds;
▪ Performance Bonds;
▪ Rental Bonds;
▪ Sub-Contractor Bonds; and
▪ Supply Bonds.

The general underwriting information is as follows:
▪ duration that the contractor has been in business;
▪ contractor’s reputation in the industry;
▪ experience and reputation of the management and other key personnel;
▪ track records of successful performance of contracts of a similar nature to the one being applied for;
▪ information on other types of contracts undertaken; and
▪ reasons for failure to perform any contracts in the past.

A call or claim on the bond is usually made when the contractor/client is unable to meet any or all of the contractual obligations of the contract that he has entered into. There are many reasons why the contractor/client is unable to perform according to the contract. Some of the common reasons are:
▪ absence of capital reserve to face unexpected difficulties, such as increase in cost of material or labour;
▪ contractor/client is not familiar with the local conditions;
▪ sudden blocking of credit by suppliers and banks;
▪ over-expansion of operation in relation to contractor/client’s capacity; or
▪ insufficient precautions to guarantee completion of the project in the event of death or injury to the contractor/client or senior employees.

The common exclusions under a FG Insurance policy are as follows:
▪ the first amount of loss shown in the schedule of the policy as the excess in respect of any one claim;
▪ if the nature of the business of the insured is changed;
▪ loss of interest or consequential loss of any kind;
▪ if the occupation or duties of the employee are changed, or remuneration of the employee is reduced without the sanction of the company;
▪ if the precautions and checks for securing accuracy of accounts are not duly observed;
▪ loss in respect of an improper financial gain obtained by any employee in the form of salaries, fees, commissions or other benefits earned in the normal course of employment; and
▪ shortage owing to error or omission, or for any unexplained or unaccountable loss or disappearance.

On discovery of any act of default or circumstance which may give rise to a claim, the insured must:
▪ give immediate notice to the insurer on the extent and circumstances of the loss, together with the name of the employee(s) suspected or discovered;
▪ take immediate actions and all steps to prevent any further loss;
▪ follow up with the notice in writing within a stated time period; and
▪ provide all required information and supporting documentary evidence relating to the claim, without any cost to the insurer.

Money Insurance is an “All Risks” cover which covers the insured against loss or destruction of or damage to money while:
▪ in transit in the personal custody of the insured and/or persons authorised by the insured between the insured’s premises, including transit from private residence of the insured or authorised persons to the bank or post office;
▪ on the insured’s premises during business hours;
▪ on the insured’s premises, not in a safe or strongroom, out of business hours (usually with a low limit);
▪ on the insured’s premises, but secured in a locked safe or strongroom out of business hours (the key to the safe must be removed from the premises and be retained by a responsible officer);
▪ in a night safe at a bank (usually a condition will be placed, e.g. the liability of the insurer will cease at the bank’s closing time on the next business day following a deposit); and
▪ the cost of repair or replacement of the safe or strongroom being damaged, not otherwise insured directly associated with any theft or attempted theft occurring during the period of insurance. Some insurers may impose a limit on any one loss.

The general underwriting information to be obtained is as follows:
▪ the amount of money in transit annually and at any one time;
▪ the method of transporting money (e.g. the use of auxiliary police or security guards);
▪ the parties carrying or transporting the money (e.g. own employees, contract employees, foreign employees, etc.);
▪ the protection of money at the premises or elsewhere (e.g. whether they are kept in locked safe or strongroom); and
▪ the system of keeping records for the movement of money.

Other than the usual exclusions that relate to strike, riot, civil commotion, war and nuclear risks, the common exclusions specific to this class of insurance are as follows:
▪ loss from an unattended vehicle;
▪ shortages owing to clerical or accounting errors and omissions;
▪ loss or damage by, or through the collusion of, or the fraudulent embezzlement or misappropriation by the insured’s employees;
▪ loss or damage caused by burglary, housebreaking or theft, unless accompanied by forcible and violent entry into or exit from the premises; and
▪ loss from a safe or strongroom opened by a key or any duplicate, unless such keys are obtained by threats or violence.

Some of the common provisions and conditions which are specific to a Credit Insurance policy are that the insured is required to:
▪ exercise reasonable care and prudence in managing the insured risks;
▪ comply with the terms of cover as granted by the insurer;
▪ declare his insured transactions, and report any overdue payments on the insured debt; and
▪ pay premium promptly and undertake to assist in the recovery action when claims are paid.

The customarily required underwriting information is as follows:
▪ sales turnover;
▪ countries to be included within insurance coverage;
▪ credit period offered to buyers;
▪ profiles of his buyers;
▪ company’s credit management; and
▪ loss experience.

Some exclusions specific to this class of insurance are as follows:
▪ the insured’s failure to comply with the laws and regulations in force in the buyer’s country;
▪ the insured’s failure or the failure of the insured’s agent to comply with or fulfil the terms of sales contract with the buyer;
▪ losses which are more appropriately insured by other forms of insurance, such as Marine Insurance;
▪ currency fluctuation or depreciation;
▪ outbreak of war between any of the following five countries: China, France, United Kingdom, United States of America and the Russian Federation; and
▪ transactions with companies where the insured has vested interests.

PRI can cover the following situation: A company may invest overseas by establishing companies involved in items such as infrastructure, manufacturing facilities, pipelines, power stations etc. There could be investments in or loans to a joint venture or a subsidiary. Profits from the overseas ventures may be at risk. PRI provides cover to protect investments against:
▪ The host country government confiscating, expropriating, nationalising or in other ways depriving the investor of his assets. This is known as ‘CEND’ cover;
▪ Currency inconvertibility - where the investor is unable to transfer the profits, loan repayments or dividends because of government restrictions or shortages of hard currency;
▪ Political violence (PV) - politically motivated acts of violence, including terrorism, war, civil disturbances, insurrection, civil war, which result in the destruction of or damage to the property or investment;
▪ Cancellation of previously valid export licences or operating licences; and
▪ Business interruption - loss of projected profits from the business in question.

The customarily required underwriting information is as follows:
▪ details of the proposer/intending insured, e.g. name, nature of business/activities, correspondence address and contact details;
▪ details of each of the persons to be insured (employees), e.g. name, date of birth, occupation/vocation, nature of work (indoor, outdoor and whether manual work involved);
▪ category of employees/occupation;
▪ basis of coverage - sum insured;
▪ number of employees; and
▪ claims experience for the past three or five years.

Besides the claim form, depending on the types of benefits claimed, the relevant documents will include:
▪ police report of the accident (if involving malicious intent);
▪ death certificate (for death benefit claim);
▪ medical report and inpatient hospital discharge summary (to certify disablement and hospitalisation treatment); and
▪ medical certificates and original medical and hospital bills, invoices and receipts (for claiming medical expense reimbursements, as well as daily hospital income benefits if covered under the group policy).
